Step 4: Click Generate and treat the output as a baseline, not the finish line

• Click Generate.

• Copy the code into your repo as something like walmart.com_scraper_v1.js will be downloaded.

• Commit early. You want diffs when you harden and when things break later.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Step 5: Check the output “score” like it’s a CI signal
I’m going to be blunt: scoring is only useful if you use it operationally. Think “parse completeness” and “data accuracy,” not vanity points.
My run looked like this:

• Total time: 4 minutes

• Data accuracy: 9.8

• Critical fields: 9.5

• Data types: 10.0

• Structure: 10.0

• Completeness: 9.0 (missed some high-res image URLs from __NEXT_DATA__)
That last line is the kind of thing that becomes a production incident if you’re not careful. You change image processing later, and suddenly you’re piping thumbnails into a downstream system that expects hero images.
