How to run a vibe coded Walmart product scraper (Node.js + Puppeteer)
1) Save the generated code
Copy/Download the generated code into walmart.com_scraper_v1.js.
2) Install dependencies
From your project directory:
npm install puppeteer-extra puppeteer-extra-plugin-stealth cheerio
3) Run the scraper
node walmart.com_scraper_v1.js
What the scraper outputs (example JSON)
The generated web scraper pulled structured product information into json: name, productId, price, preDiscountPrice, availability, seller, images, specifications, review data / reviews, and more. That’s the core of walmart product data data extraction and a solid start for price monitoring or catalog analytics. In other words: we’ll scrape walmart product data and keep it consistent — same fields, same meaning, run after run.
If you inspect a typical walmart product page, you’ll usually find multiple sources of web data: rendered HTML, embedded application state (often as json), and XHR responses. Your extractor can choose the most stable source; many teams prefer the embedded json for critical product details like identifiers and offer price, then fall back to DOM selectors if needed. This is often where the “hidden web data” lives, and it can be more stable than scraping raw HTML nodes.
If you need a shortcut for turning messy HTML into structured JSON for common targets, there are also parser services like Parser API that can help on some sites. I still prefer owning my extractors for key workflows, but having a fallback can reduce downtime when walmart page markup drifts.
